✅ FIX (HTTPS method — most common)
1. Fully remove cached GitHub login

Run this in Git Bash:

printf "protocol=https\nhost=github.com\n" | git credential-manager-core erase
2. Also remove saved Windows credentials (VERY IMPORTANT)

On Windows:

Open Control Panel
Go to Credential Manager
Click Windows Credentials
Delete anything like:
git:https://github.com
github.com
3. Check your remote (just to confirm)
git remote -v

Make sure it is:

https://github.com/yenaung1001/Test-1001.git

If not:

git remote set-url origin https://github.com/yenaung1001/Test-1001.git
4. Push again (this forces re-login)
git push -u origin main

Now Git will ask:

Username → yenaung1001
Password → GitHub Personal Access Token (NOT password)
🔑 IMPORTANT: Use Personal Access Token

On GitHub:

Settings → Developer settings → Tokens
Create token with repo permission

Paste that as password.

⚠️ If it STILL uses yenaung56

That means Windows is still auto-filling credentials.

Run:

git config --global credential.helper manager-core

Then retry push.

🚀 BEST LONG-TERM FIX (recommended)

Switch to SSH so this never happens again:

git remote set-url origin git@github.com:yenaung1001/Test-1001.git

Then you authenticate once with SSH key and never deal with 403 again.

